      "role": "user",
      "content": "the logging approach makes sense, but the issue is the system is quite resource-constrained so heavy logging might tank the real-time performance. it feels like the leak is just hiding in a corner somewhere, appearing and disappearing in different modules. do you have any suggestions for more passive ways to pinpoint where these orphaned allocations are coming from without flooding the bus?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If heavy logging is too much, you need a more stealthy approach, like tracking the *behavior* of the memory rather than logging every single transaction. You can use memory profiling techniques that are less intrusive, which is crucial in a resource-constrained environment. Think of it like tracking a single, tiny, persistent shadow in a dark workshop—you don't want to shine a floodlight everywhere, just a focused beam.\n\nSince you're in C++, the best passive methods involve wrapping your memory management functions. Instead of logging *every* call, you can implement custom allocators or use memory hooks to track *where* the memory is being requested, without necessarily storing every single allocation detail in a massive log buffer.\n\nHere are a few passive strategies:\n\n1.  **Custom Overloaded `new`/`delete` Operators:** This is the most direct method. You can overload the global `operator new` and `operator delete` (or overload them within specific classes if you suspect a module). Instead of logging the full context, your overloaded functions can simply increment a counter associated with the *call stack* or the *module ID* that initiated the allocation. When the system runs, you check which module ID's",
      "source": "target",
